  "insights": {
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Coverage improved, especially for zero-dose status",
        "body": "Among children aged 12 to 23 months, full basic-antigen vaccination rose from 71.8 percent in 2022 to 77.1 percent in 2025. Full national-schedule vaccination also rose, from 59.4 to 62.4 percent. The largest movement is in no vaccinations, which fell from 11.2 percent to 5.7 percent."
      },
      {
        "heading": "The national schedule remains the harder threshold",
        "body": "In 2025, 77.1 percent of children were fully vaccinated for basic antigens, but only 62.4 percent were fully vaccinated according to the national schedule. The 14.7-point gap shows that many children receive the core basic set but do not complete the broader schedule required by the national definition."
      },
      {
        "heading": "BARMM is the major regional outlier",
        "body": "BARMM had 22.1 percent full basic-antigen coverage and 13.0 percent full national-schedule coverage, far below the national levels. It also had the highest no-vaccination share at 28.1 percent. Zamboanga Peninsula was also low, with 61.7 percent basic coverage, 42.1 percent national-schedule coverage, and 20.3 percent no vaccinations."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Ilocos Region combines high completion with no zero-dose children",
        "body": "Ilocos Region led both completion measures, with 95.6 percent full basic-antigen coverage and 94.3 percent full national-schedule coverage. It also recorded 0.0 percent no vaccinations. Negros Island Region likewise recorded 0.0 percent no vaccinations, but its full national-schedule coverage was lower than Ilocos, showing that zero-dose reduction and full completion are related but not identical."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Card status strongly separates reported completion",
        "body": "Vaccination card status is one of the most important interpretive variables on this page. Children with cards seen usually show much higher recorded completion than children whose cards were not seen or who never had a card. This pattern should be read as a measurement and service-contact signal, not as proof of cause by itself."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Regional divides are larger than most household gradients",
        "body": "The regional spread in full national-schedule coverage runs from 94.3 percent in Ilocos Region to 13.0 percent in BARMM. That gap is much wider than typical differences by sex, residence, or wealth on this page. The national average therefore hides a highly uneven regional vaccination landscape."
      }
    ],
    "takeaways": [
      "Full vaccination improved from 2022 to 2025, and no-vaccination status fell by about half.",
      "The national schedule remains harder to complete than the basic-antigen set.",
      "BARMM and Zamboanga Peninsula are the clearest regional concerns, especially for full-schedule completion and no vaccinations.",
      "Ilocos Region shows the strongest completion profile, with very high full-schedule coverage and no recorded zero-dose children."
    ]
  }
